Dialogue: 0,0:00:00.00,0:00:06.30,Default,,0,0,0,,This is a concept OpenLayers application created to test animated WMS layers provided by GeoServer's WMS animator
Dialogue: 0,0:00:06.57,0:00:11.08,Default,,0,0,0,,Users can visualize the evolution of maximum temperatures over a period of 7 days
Dialogue: 0,0:00:11.08,0:00:16.01,Default,,0,0,0,,Rendering an animated WMS layer is a costly operation for GeoServer
Dialogue: 0,0:00:22.10,0:00:28.48,Default,,0,0,0,,Users can visualize the evolution of specific temperature ranges
Dialogue: 0,0:00:48.82,0:00:56.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's visualize other temperature ranges in a warmer period...
Dialogue: 0,0:01:08.73,0:01:14.17,Default,,0,0,0,,An even warmer period...
Dialogue: 0,0:01:15.68,0:01:20.99,Default,,0,0,0,,Animations are orchestrated by the aparams and avalues parameters
Dialogue: 0,0:01:20.99,0:01:25.35,Default,,0,0,0,,The aparams controls which WMS property will be the basis of the animation
Dialogue: 0,0:01:25.35,0:01:30.14,Default,,0,0,0,,The avalues defines the value of this property for each frame of the animation
Dialogue: 0,0:01:30.14,0:01:33.20,Default,,0,0,0,,In this application I defined aparams as cql_filter
Dialogue: 0,0:01:33.20,0:01:38.02,Default,,0,0,0,,Which implies that for every frame of the animation, a CQL query has to be specified
Dialogue: 0,0:01:47.25,0:01:50.75,Default,,0,0,0,,Interpolations were rendered at a very low resolution (600x259)
Dialogue: 0,0:01:50.75,0:02:00.88,Default,,0,0,0,,So edges are bound to look jagged if zooming forces the layer to be rendered beyond its native resolution (this has nothing to do with the animator)
Dialogue: 0,0:02:04.12,0:02:10.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Behavior of animated WMS layers is identical to their static counterparts in OpenLayers...
Dialogue: 0,0:02:33.68,0:02:36.25,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's test a full screen animation...
